  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A cash flow statement tracks the actual movement of money into and out of a business over a defined period. Unlike the income statement, which records revenue when it is earned and expenses when they are incurred (accrual accounting), the cash flow statement records when money actually changes hands. A business can be profitable on its income statement and still run out of cash — if customers pay late, if inventory must be purchased in advance, or if a large expense comes due before revenue arrives.\n",
